african american arts winter lecture series leigh raiford african american arts winter lecture series leigh raiford marcus garvey in stereograph james vanderzee the unia and the photographic practices of diaspora how has photography worked to articulate to join up and express the african diaspora through an interrogation of images of pan africanist leader marcus garvey his universal negro improvement association unia and the organization's commission of harlem studio portraitist james vanderzee this paper explores the constitution of african diasporic subjectivity black modernity and modes of seeing and feeling transnational blackness leigh raiford ph d yale university 2003 is assistant professor at the department of african american studies at uc berkeley and is affiliated faculty in the department of gender and women's studies american studies program and the berkeley center for new media more information date and time tuesday february 9 2010 5 00 pm approximate duration of 1.5 hour s location annenberg auditorium map audience faculty staff general public students category lectures readings sponsor department of art & art history contact 650 723 3404 risip stanford edu admission free and open to the public download add to personal calendar vcal record email event print use this permalink last modified february 1 2010
